<TITLE> EU placates Austria in student quota row </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, Oct 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The European Commission will suspend legal action against Austria over foreign student quotas at medical schools, the EU executive said on Wednesday, after the issue threatened to cloud the bloc's summit this week. German-speaking Austria imposed the curbs because it is flooded with medical students from its bigger neighbour, Germany, who were unable to study in their own country because of "numerus clausus" restrictions on student places. The Commission said Austria had presented data which indicate its health system could suffer without quotas at medical universities for foreigners, who usually leave the country after graduation. "We are preparing a decision on the suspension to be taken in coming weeks by the Commission," Commission President Jose Manuel Barroso told a news conference. Austria will have to provide more information about its health and medical education systems before the Commission can decide whether it will close the disciplinary procedure. The EU executive's declaration came a day before the EU's 27 leaders meet in Lisbon to approve a new treaty to overhaul the bloc's often inefficient institutions. At an EU foreign ministers' meeting on Monday, Austria demanded the treaty be formulated in such a way as to allow for student quotas, creating another hurdle for the smooth adoption of the charter. The Commission said Austria's 25 percent quota of foreign students was incompatible with EU laws on freedom of movement of people and challenged it at the European Court of Justice. The court confirmed the Austrian system breached EU l
